---
// waitpoint-base-topology — Chapter 066 Lesson 6, "Waitpoints for callbacks and approvals".
//
// The base case of the whole primitive: one run, one token, one completer. The
// figure makes the four-beat lifecycle (create → park → complete → resume) legible
// as a single closed loop so the three later workflow shapes read as the same
// picture from different angles.
//
//   Run  ──park──▶  Token  ◀──complete──  Completer (HTTP / SDK / timeout)
//    ▲                 │
//    └─────resume──────┘   (bows BELOW the boxes, separate lane from park)
//
// "park" and "resume" are the cyclic pair between the same two boxes — the
// ArrowDiagram doc says a side-by-side gap can't hold both curves, so they live in
// two lanes: park rides the top sockets in the upper gap, resume leaves the token's
// bottom and lands on the run's bottom, bowing downward so it never crosses park.
// "complete" is the external signal — green — flowing back INTO the token from the
// completer on the right.
//
// Built with <ArrowDiagram> (LeaderLine): the completer box is custom HTML (a title
// plus three chips), and the per-arrow coloring (neutral park/resume vs green
// external complete) is the point — plain-label D2/Mermaid boxes wouldn't carry it.
// Arrows are positioned from document.body, so the wrapping <Figure> MUST be
// expandable={false}; relocating the body into the lightbox breaks the leader lines.

import Figure from '../../../figures/Figure.astro';
import ArrowDiagram from '../../../figures/ArrowDiagram.astro';

// Mid-tone accents reused verbatim in light + dark.
const NEUTRAL = '#64748b'; // slate-500 — the runtime-owned park/resume lifecycle
const GREEN = '#16a34a'; // green-600 — the external signal that completes the token

const arrows = [
	// park: run → token, upper lane. Leaves the run's right (top), lands on the
	// token's left (top), so the curve sits in the upper part of the gap.
	{
		from: 'wp-run',
		to: 'wp-token',
		label: 'park',
		color: NEUTRAL,
		startSocket: 'top',
		endSocket: 'top',
		startSocketGravity: [60, -28],
		endSocketGravity: [-60, -28],
		labelOffset: [0, -14],
	},
	// complete: completer → token, the external signal flowing back into the token.
	// Green to mark it as the outside-world beat.
	{
		from: 'wp-completer',
		to: 'wp-token',
		label: 'complete',
		color: GREEN,
		startSocket: 'left',
		endSocket: 'right',
		startSocketGravity: [-70, 0],
		endSocketGravity: [70, 0],
		labelOffset: [0, -16],
	},
	// resume: token → run, lower lane. Leaves the token's bottom, lands on the run's
	// bottom, bowing downward below the boxes so it never crosses the park arrow.
	{
		from: 'wp-token',
		to: 'wp-run',
		label: 'resume',
		color: NEUTRAL,
		startSocket: 'bottom',
		endSocket: 'bottom',
		startSocketGravity: [-60, 70],
		endSocketGravity: [60, 70],
		labelOffset: [0, 16],
	},
];

const chips = ['Third party (HTTP)', 'Human (SDK call)', 'Timeout'];
---

<Figure expandable={false}>
	<ArrowDiagram arrows={arrows}>
		<div class="wp not-content">
			<div class="wp-box" id="wp-run">
				<span class="wp-title">Run</span>
				<span class="wp-under">parks on token</span>
			</div>
			<div class="wp-box wp-token" id="wp-token">
				<span class="wp-title">Waitpoint token</span>
				<span class="wp-under">durable pause</span>
			</div>
			<div class="wp-completer-col">
				<div class="wp-box" id="wp-completer">
					<span class="wp-title">Completed by…</span>
				</div>
				<div class="wp-chips">
					{chips.map((chip) => <span class="wp-chip">{chip}</span>)}
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</ArrowDiagram>
	<Fragment slot="caption">
		One run parks on one token, and any one of three completers — a third party's
		HTTP callback, a human's SDK-backed click, or the timeout — wakes it. The
		topology generalizes both ways: many runs could listen on a single token, and
		one run could wait on several tokens at once. That second direction — wait for
		*all* of N — is built later in this lesson with `batchTriggerAndWait`.
	</Fragment>
</Figure>

<style>
	.wp {
		display: flex;
		flex-wrap: nowrap;
		align-items: flex-start;
		justify-content: space-between;
		gap: 110px;
		margin: 0;
		/* Extra top + bottom padding reserves the lanes the park/resume curves bow
		   into above and below the boxes. */
		padding: 40px 8px 48px;
		font-family:
			ui-sans-serif, system-ui, -apple-system, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, sans-serif;
	}

	.wp-box {
		box-sizing: border-box;
		display: flex;
		flex-direction: column;
		align-items: center;
		gap: 3px;
		flex: 0 1 auto;
		padding: 11px 16px;
		border-radius: 10px;
		border: 1px solid var(--sl-color-gray-5, #cbd5e1);
		background: var(--sl-color-bg, transparent);
		text-align: center;
		margin: 0;
	}

	/* The token is the hub of the loop — tint it so the eye lands there first. */
	.wp-token {
		border-color: color-mix(in srgb, #64748b 45%, var(--sl-color-gray-5, #cbd5e1));
		background: color-mix(in srgb, #64748b 8%, var(--sl-color-bg, transparent));
	}

	.wp-title {
		font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Monaco, Consolas, monospace;
		font-size: 0.86rem;
		font-weight: 600;
		line-height: 1.2;
		white-space: nowrap;
		color: var(--sl-color-white, #1e293b);
		margin: 0;
	}

	.wp-under {
		font-size: 0.66rem;
		line-height: 1.2;
		white-space: nowrap;
		color: var(--sl-color-gray-3, #64748b);
		margin: 0;
	}

	.wp-completer-col {
		display: flex;
		flex-direction: column;
		align-items: center;
		gap: 8px;
		flex: 0 1 auto;
		margin: 0;
	}

	.wp-chips {
		display: flex;
		flex-direction: column;
		gap: 5px;
		align-items: stretch;
	}

	.wp-chip {
		font-size: 0.68rem;
		line-height: 1.2;
		white-space: nowrap;
		text-align: center;
		padding: 4px 10px;
		border-radius: 999px;
		border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, #16a34a 35%, transparent);
		background: color-mix(in srgb, #16a34a 12%, transparent);
		color: var(--sl-color-white, #166534);
		margin: 0;
	}

	/* Narrow viewports: stack the three columns. The top/bottom sockets degrade to
	   vertical arcs between stacked boxes — readable, and the labels still float. */
	@media (max-width: 720px) {
		.wp {
			flex-direction: column;
			align-items: center;
			gap: 64px;
			padding: 20px 8px;
		}
		.wp-box {
			width: min(18rem, 100%);
		}
	}
</style>
